This paper deals with kernel principal component analysis, which is a common technique in machine learning and data analysis. The paper focuses on the statistical and computational aspects of this technique, which suggests that it is likely to fall under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper proposes a memory-efficient streaming algorithm, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of random Fourier features and the analysis of sample complexity suggest that the paper may also fall under the categories of cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper's focus on kernel methods and their implementation suggests that it may also fall under the category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
